1Ô∏è‚É£ What is the 0/1 Knapsack Problem? (Very simple words)

Imagine:

You have a bag (knapsack) that can carry limited weight

You have items, each item has:

Weight

Value (profit)

You want to maximize total value

You cannot break items

You either take the whole item or don‚Äôt take it

üëâ 0/1 means:

0 ‚Üí not taken

1 ‚Üí taken

Example (Real-life thinking)
Item	Weight	Value
A	1	10
B	2	15
C	3	40

Knapsack capacity = 5

Goal:
üëâ Pick items so that total weight ‚â§ 5
üëâ Total value is maximum

2Ô∏è‚É£ Criteria / Rules to follow (Very Important)

You MUST follow these rules in 0/1 Knapsack:

‚úÖ Rule 1: Each item can be used only once

You cannot repeat the same item

‚úÖ Rule 2: Item is either taken or not taken

No partial selection

You can‚Äôt take half an item

‚úÖ Rule 3: Total weight must not exceed capacity

If capacity is 5, weight must be ‚â§ 5

‚úÖ Rule 4: Goal is to maximize value, not weight

Weight is a constraint

Value is the target

3Ô∏è‚É£ Why do we use Dynamic Programming (DP)?
Problem with brute force

If you try all combinations, time becomes very large (2‚Åø).

DP idea (simple language)

‚ÄúSolve small problems first and reuse their answers‚Äù

We build a table where:

Rows ‚Üí items

Columns ‚Üí knapsack capacity

4Ô∏è‚É£ DP Table Meaning (Most Important Part)

Let:

dp[i][w]
Meaning:

Maximum value we can get using first i items with capacity w

DP decision logic (heart of the problem)

For each item:

1Ô∏è‚É£ If item weight > current capacity
‚û° Cannot take it
‚û° Copy previous value

dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]

2Ô∏è‚É£ If item weight ‚â§ current capacity
‚û° Choose maximum of:

Not taking item

Taking item

dp[i][w] = max(
    dp[i-1][w],                      // not take
    value[i] + dp[i-1][w - weight[i]] // take
)
5Ô∏è‚É£ Visual DP Table (Conceptual)

Example capacity = 5
Items = 3

        Capacity ‚Üí
Items ‚Üì   0  1  2  3  4  5
--------------------------------
0 items   0  0  0  0  0  0
Item 1    0 10 10 10 10 10
Item 2    0 10 15 25 25 25
Item 3    0 10 15 40 50 55  ‚úÖ

üëâ Final answer = dp[3][5] = 55